{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17532768","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17532768"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:30:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:30:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14718"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14718","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14718"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.02,0.44,0.01,0.5]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7411"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109127"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7411","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7411"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14718"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91486"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"461"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"1544"},{"type":"tags","id":"5585"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18086"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31380"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40742"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109127","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109127"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a one month history of progressive pain and difficulty on swallowing solid foods. She started radiation therapy for oesophageal cancer two months ago. She has lost 1 kg in weight. She takes regular paracetamol and ondansetron. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her body mass index is 19 kg/m2. The remainder of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Tumour recurrence","Candida oesophagitis","Radiation-induced stricture","Gastro-oesophageal reflux disease","Radiation-induced oesophagitis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with progressive dysphagia two months after commencing radiation therapy for oesophageal cancer. The timing and nature of symptoms are most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Eradiation-induced oesophagitis.\u003C/strong\u003E This is an early complication that typically occurs during or shortly after treatment (within 90 days). It may present as odynophagia, chest pain or dysphagia. It usually improves after completion of therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadiation-induced stricture\u003C/strong\u003E typically develops months to years after treatment due to progressive fibrosis and is a common late complication of radiation therapy to the oesophagus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETumour recurrence\u003C/strong\u003E is always a concern in cancer survivors and should be investigated. However, the gradual onset of symptoms and timing are more typical of radiation-induced oesophagitis though it would still be needed to be ruled out.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECandida oesophagitis\u003C/strong\u003E can occur in patients who have received radiation therapy but typically presents with pain on swallowing and white plaques visible on endoscopy. The progressive nature of symptoms makes this less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastro-oesophageal reflux disease\u003C/strong\u003E can cause dysphagia but would be unlikely to cause such significant progressive symptoms in this timeframe without other typical symptoms such as heartburn.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Early radiation complications typically occur within 90 days of treatment and include mucositis, dermatitis, and nausea.","The risk and severity of radiation complications depends on total dose, fractionation schedule, and tissue radiosensitivity."],"references":["Di Muzio B, Murphy A, Yap J, et al. Radiation-induced esophagitis. Reference article, Radiopaedia.org.  2019.  Available at: https://radiopaedia.org/articles/radiation-induced-oesophagitis?lang=us","Baker S, Fairchild A. Radiation-induced esophagitis in lung cancer. Lung Cancer (Auckl). 2016 Oct 13;7:119-127. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28210168/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91486"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14718"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91486","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91486"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-17T20:30:32+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-17T20:31:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7411"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109127"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data"